  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_2",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: free-running period. How to measure the endogenous period (tau) of a rhythm running without a zeitgeber (e.g. constant darkness). Step 1 — the actogram is the diagnostic view: it is double-plotted (two cycles side by side) against a 24 h grid, so a rhythm whose tau differs from 24 h shows as a band DRIFTING steadily across days rather than sitting vertical. Drift to the right = tau > 24 h; to the left = tau < 24 h. Step 2 — the periodogram estimates tau numerically: this demo uses Lomb-Scargle, which handles unevenly sampled data and is the recommended default. Step 3 — the Rhythmicity Analysis node reports the peak period as a wireable number (shown in the table), so it can feed a group comparison. IMPORTANT — method choice: avoid the chi-square (Sokolove-Bushell) periodogram as a first choice; it systematically UNDERESTIMATES period in a way that depends on the true period and record length, and Lomb-Scargle or a padded FFT are more accurate (Tackenberg & Hughey 2021). Record length and noise matter far more than sampling frequency: ~5+ days is a reasonable minimum, and a baseline trend should be detrended before estimating period (Zielinski et al. 2014).",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
